# Understanding Classes in TypeScript

## Introduction

Classes are one of the core features of TypeScript and provide a clean way to create reusable, maintainable, and object-oriented code.

In backend applications, classes are commonly used for:

* Entities
* Services
* Repositories
* Controllers
* Use Cases
* DTO Mapping

Understanding classes is essential before learning frameworks such as NestJS or implementing Clean Architecture.

---

## What is a Class?

A class is a blueprint used to create objects.

Example:

```ts
class User {
  name: string;

  constructor(name: string) {
    this.name = name;
  }
}

const user = new User("Milad");

console.log(user.name);
```

Output:

```txt
Milad
```

---

## Properties

Properties store data inside an object.

```ts
class Product {
  title: string;
  price: number;

  constructor(title: string, price: number) {
    this.title = title;
    this.price = price;
  }
}
```

---

## Methods

Methods define behavior.

```ts
class Product {
  title: string;
  price: number;

  constructor(title: string, price: number) {
    this.title = title;
    this.price = price;
  }

  getPrice() {
    return this.price;
  }
}
```

---

## Access Modifiers

TypeScript supports three access levels:

### Public

Accessible everywhere.

```ts
public name: string;
```

### Private

Accessible only inside the class.

```ts
private password: string;
```

### Protected

Accessible inside the class and subclasses.

```ts
protected salary: number;
```

---

## Constructor Shortcut

```ts
class User {
  constructor(
    public name: string,
    public age: number
  ) {}
}
```

Instead of:

```ts
class User {
  name: string;
  age: number;

  constructor(name: string, age: number) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }
}
```

---

## Inheritance

```ts
class Animal {
  move() {
    console.log("Moving...");
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  bark() {
    console.log("Woof!");
  }
}
```

---

## Abstract Classes

Useful for backend architecture.

```ts
abstract class Repository {
  abstract findById(id: number): Promise<any>;
}
```

---

## Interfaces vs Classes

| Feature         | Interface | Class |
| --------------- | --------- | ----- |
| Type Definition | ✅         | ✅     |
| Implementation  | ❌         | ✅     |
| Constructor     | ❌         | ✅     |
| Inheritance     | Limited   | Full  |

---

## Real Backend Example

Service Layer:

```ts
class UserService {
  async findUser(id: number) {
    return { id };
  }
}
```

Repository Layer:

```ts
class UserRepository {
  async findById(id: number) {
    return db.users.find(id);
  }
}
```

Controller Layer:

```ts
class UserController {
  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}

  async getUser(id: number) {
    return this.userService.findUser(id);
  }
}
```

---

## Common Mistakes

* Overusing classes for simple data structures
* Exposing sensitive fields as public
* Mixing business logic and database logic
* Forgetting to use interfaces with classes

